  "doc_id": "17766",
  "text": "All rats were immunized intraperitoneally (IP) with the soluble protein antigen KLH (300 g/kg KLH ammonium sulfate slurry; Calbiochem, La Jolla, CA) in sterile phosphate-buffered saline (PBS; Sigma Chemical Co., St. Louis, MO). Previous research in our laboratory has shown that a 300-g/kg dose of KLH induces robust antibody responses [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Blood samples for titration of antibody were obtained 1 day before the experimental manipulation (day 0) and again on days 3, 5, 7, 11, and 14 after immunization using a modification of a simple tail venipuncture method for bleeding unanesthetized rats [CITATION_3] . This method does not produce physical trauma, and repeated blood sampling of up to 1 ml does not alter corticosterone levels compared with levels found in naive animals [CITATION_4] . Briefly, rats were restrained, the tail was briefly immersed in warm water, and a 23-gauge needle was inserted into a vessel in the midventral surface of the tail. Blood (approximately 0.3 ml) was collected using unheparinized microcapillary tubes and spun in a hematocrit centrifuge for 15 minutes to obtain serum. Aliquots of serum were diluted 1:10 with 0.05% Tween-20 in PBS and stored at Ϫ80°C for subsequent analysis by enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA).",
